***** WIP Cleanups
******* DONE Some docstrings talk of EXPRESSIONS, some of FORMS.
******* DONE "Yields" vs "returns" a value.
******* DONE Restricts vs constrains.
        Public docstrings normalised to "constrain"; "restrict-X!"
        function names retained as internal API.
******* DONE Don't talk about noticers: they're an implementation detail.
        Noticer mentions removed from public docstrings (integerpv,
        rationalpv, ratiopv, floatpv, realpv, numberpv, memberv, notv,
        andv, orv, equalv, =v, <v, /=v, known?, assert!, decide).
        Bidirectional propagation now described as "mutually
        constrained" without exposing the noticer mechanism.
***** DONE Simplify the language in the constraint section.
      Constraint-section docstrings condensed: redundant per-direction
      noticer paragraphs replaced with concise "mutually constrained"
      statements. Manual texinfo prose was already clean.
* DONE Port LOCAL-OUTPUT to SLIME.
    New screamer-slime.el replaces iscream.el for the Emacs side and
    auto-enables slime-enable-evaluate-in-emacs on load.
    EMACS-EVAL now uses SWANK:EVAL-IN-EMACS instead of escape codes.
    LOCAL-OUTPUT now captures *standard-output* during the body and
    sends the text to the *Screamer Output* buffer via
    screamer-slime-insert-output; trail closures call
    screamer-slime-pop-end-marker on backtrack to delete the inserted
    text. Live-observation tool only; the buffer is fully unwound
    when the search exits (ALL-VALUES exhaustion or ONE-VALUE return).
    *ISCREAM?* kept as the explicit gate. Y-OR-N-P simplified to
    delegate to CL:Y-OR-N-P (SLIME routes to the minibuffer
    natively). iscream.el deleted.
* DONE Screamer 5 imports
    Imported from Swapneil Singh's Screamer 5 (verbatim unless noted):
    - WITH-TRAIL macro for pre-allocating *trail* in long searches.
    - COPY-OUTPUT-VALUE typecase deep-copy: cons (copy-tree),
      hash-table (alexandria:copy-hash-table with source-side
      iteration), sequence (copy-seq), structure-object (copy-structure).
      ALL-VALUES and N-VALUES apply it to every collected value
      unconditionally so trail-unwind cannot mutate already-collected
      results.
    - VARIABLE-DEPENDENCIES slot on the variable defstruct, plus
      ATTACH-NOTICER! :DEPENDENCIES keyword and
      ATTACH-DEPENDENCIES!-INTERNAL helper.
    - MAPCAR-NONDETERMINISTIC.
    - SCREAMER-ERROR condition class with MESSAGE and ARGS slots.
    - DEFINE-CONDITION-COMPILE-TIME and DEFPARAMETER-COMPILE-TIME
      macros, mirroring the existing DEFUN-/DEFMACRO-/DEFVAR-COMPILE-TIME
      infrastructure.
    Refined locally:
    - STATIC-ORDERING-INTERNAL rewritten to recurse into a variable's
      dependencies inline before forcing it.
    - DOMAIN-SIZE integer branch fixed to handle non-integer-bound
      ranges via (1+ (- (floor U) (ceiling L))) (the Screamer 5 5.2.2
      patch handled integer bounds only).
* DONE Arithmetic propagation refactor
    --RULE-UP and /-RULE-UP added symmetric to +-RULE-UP and *-RULE-UP.
    Float-to-nonrational guard in +-RULE-DOWN and *-RULE-DOWN tightened
    from (or float-z float-y) to (and float-z rational-y).
    Numeric-type helpers NUMERIC-TYPE-TAG, CONTAGIOUS-ZERO,
    IDENTITY-SHORTCUT-SAFE? introduced and used by the refactored +V2,
    -V2, *V2, /V2. Noticer-attach path of *V2 and /V2 extracted into
    GENERAL-*V2 and GENERAL-/V2. /V2 cond order corrected: (zerop y)
    -> (fail) now precedes (zerop x) -> 0.
* DONE TYPES propagation through CPS
    CPS-CONVERT-CALL and CPS-CONVERT-MULTIPLE-VALUE-CALL-INTERNAL
    propagate the TYPES parameter to the continuation: magic
    continuations receive a (the (and ...) ...) wrap via
    INJECT-TYPE-INTO-MAGIC-CONTINUATION; literal #'foo or
    uninterned-symbol continuations route through
    WRAP-RUNTIME-THE-CONTINUATION.
* DONE LispWorks Personal docstring re-installation
    LispWorks Personal Edition's compiler discards docstrings during
    the SCREAMER:DEFUN force-compile pass. FUNCTION-DEFINITION now
    emits an explicit (setf (documentation NAME 'function) DOC) under
    #+lispworks in both the deterministic and nondeterministic
    branches when a docstring is present. Hobbyist/Professional/
    Enterprise editions do not exhibit the stripping.
* TODO Rewrite dynamic-extent continuations using FLET
    POSSIBLY-BETA-REDUCE-FUNCALL currently emits LET for magic-cont
    sites. Switching to FLET aliasing would enable stack-allocation
    of continuation closures on SBCL (which cannot stack-allocate
    LET-bound lambdas but can stack-allocate FLET-bound functions).
* DONE Dynamic-extent in CPS-CONVERT-TAGBODY.
    LABELS-bound continuations declared (dynamic-extent ...).
* WIP Split the system into logical pieces.
    Most of the DEFUN-COMPILE-TIME functions should probably go
    to a file of their own, loaded before the main screamer code
    is compiled.
* TODO Cleanups
*** DONE #:DUMMY-N gensyms used all over the place
    Renamed by role across CPS sites: OLD-/NEW- (trail save vs new
    value), TEST- (IF antecedent), LET-VALUE- (LET binding),
    MV- (multi-value &rest list), FN-VALUE- (multiple-value-call
    function), ARG- (call argument), IGNORED- (discarded args).
*** DONE DEFMACRO-COMPILE-TIME
      Check if Allegro still needs this.
      Used across all 4 supported impls (SBCL, CCL, LispWorks, Allegro).
*** TODO primordial.lisp has some commented-out tests using LOOP
    Apparently LOCAL and LOOP interactions depend on the specific
    expansion of loop. :/ If nothing else, documentation should
    mention this. An alternative would be to provide our own
    implementation of LOOP that is well-behaved when it comes to
    LOCAL. The walker currently signals an explicit error for LOOP
    in nondeterministic context (see WALK function).
*** TODO review the remaining limitations listed in the old source, and put the in the manual
     1. Does not handle SETF methods with multiple values for LOCAL
        SETF.
     2. If you do a (SETF (SYMBOL-FUNCTION 'FOO) ...) to a nondeterministic
	function you will lose when you attempt to evaluate (FOO ...).
     3. If you do a (SETF (SYMBOL-FUNCTION 'FOO) ...) to a deterministic
	function when FOO was previously defined as a nondeterministic
	function you will lose when you attempt to evaluate (FOO ...).
     4. TODO: FLET and LABELS in nondeterministic context currently
        signal "Cannot (currently) handle the special form" because
        cps-convert has no FLET/LABELS clause. A cps-convert-flet/
        labels implementation plus a *lexical-function-records* alist
        would route calls to labels-bound nondet names through their
        CPS form.
     5. There is no way to force Screamer into compiling a deterministic
	function as a nondeterministic one. A wizard might want to do this to
	take advantage of the fact that a LOCAL SETF/SETQ in a nondeterministic
	function does not cons up closures.
* Bugs
*** TODO LOCAL only reliable with explicit SETF/SETQ:
    If (INCF (FOO)) expands into a form that does SET-FOO instead of
    (SETF (FOO) ...) form, the code walker will not know about the
    side-effect.

    Options:
    - Implement SCREAMER:INCF, etc.
    - Wrap all non-SETF/SETQ forms in GLOBAL, so that those side-effects are never undone.
    - Leave it as-is.
* Old "Bugs to fix" list from screamer.lisp
  These haven't been verified or anything, just moved here.
*** TODO Deterministic/nondeterministic LOCAL SETF/SETQ undone out of order.
    No regression test or repro available; bug is unverified in 4.0.1.
    Needs a deliberate failing example before acting.
*** TODO Changing determinism status
    can cause code from a different file to be included causing wierd behavior.
*** TODO May loop when expressions contain circular lists.
    Confirmed still present in 4.0.1: occurs-in?, attach-noticer!-internal,
    attach-dependencies!-internal carry "Will loop if X is circular" notes.
    apply-substitution/contains-variables? have no cycle guard either.
    Preserved behaviour from upstream; circular Screamer expressions are
    rare in practice.
*** DONE APPLY-NONDETERMINISTIC conses.
    Reduced via (apply #'apply ...) flattening in
    apply-nondeterministic-nondeterministic.
